âœ… What to Keep in Mind Before Validating API Requests
When testing APIs, you should think from functional, non-functional, and security perspectives.
ðŸ”¹ 1. Functional Validation (Basic Checks)
HTTP Status Codes â†’ Correct code for request (200 OK, 201 Created, 400 Bad Request, 401 Unauthorized,
                    404 Not Found, 500 Server Error).
Response Body â†’ Validate schema, fields, data types, mandatory fields.
Response Headers â†’ Content-Type, caching headers, security headers (X-Frame-Options, CORS).
Request Payload â†’ Validate correct format (JSON/XML), required fields, boundary values.
Idempotency â†’ Same request should give consistent results (e.g., PUT vs POST).
Error Handling â†’ Proper error messages with error codes.

ðŸ”¹ 2. Integration Validation
Contract Testing â†’ Request/response follows agreed schema between services.
Database State â†’ DB changes are correct after API call.
Upstream/Downstream Dependencies â†’ API should handle dependent service failures gracefully 
(timeouts, retries, fallbacks).

Workflow Scenarios â†’ For example, Expedia booking API should ensure that payment triggers booking confirmation.
ðŸ”¹ 3. Non-Functional Validation
Performance â†’ Response time under SLA (e.g., <200ms for search API).
Load & Scalability â†’ API can handle concurrent requests.
Rate Limiting / Throttling â†’ API should gracefully reject when limit exceeded.
Caching â†’ Responses cached where applicable to reduce load.

ðŸ”¹ 4. Security Validation
Authentication/Authorization â†’ OAuth2, JWT, API keys validated properly.
Input Validation â†’ Prevent SQL Injection, XSS, malicious payloads.
Sensitive Data â†’ PII, credit card details must be masked or encrypted.
HTTPS Enforcement â†’ No plain HTTP allowed.
Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) â†’ Only authorized roles can access specific endpoints.

ðŸ”¹ 5. Usability & Maintainability Checks
Versioning â†’ API should handle backward compatibility (/v1/, /v2/).
Documentation â†’ Swagger/OpenAPI spec should match implementation.
Consistency â†’ Naming conventions, pagination, sorting must be uniform.

ðŸš€ Quick Checklist (for interview pitch)
ðŸ‘‰ When validating API requests, I check:
Status codes & response schema (Functional).
Headers, payloads, error handling (Functional).
Integration correctness & DB impact (Integration).
Performance, load, scalability (Non-functional).
Security: auth, encryption, input validation (Critical).
Versioning & documentation consistency (Maintainability).

âš¡ Interview Tip: End with â†’
â€œI always start with functional correctness, then validate integration flows, and finally cover
 non-functional aspects like performance and security. That ensures APIs are reliable, secure, and 
production-ready.â€
